Namespace http://ole.kuali.org/standards/ole-instance
Annotations
 
THIS IS A WORK IN PROGRESS: for actual schema and comments, see https://gist.github.com/adamc-ole/7472860
            
This schema describes a basic document type for bibliographic data about items and holdings in OLE.
            
It is primarily intended to serve as a guideline for governing data interchange between systems 
(particularly initial ingest and for use in providing information to discovery systems), and 
does not directly describe any storage mechanism or UI element.  
            
This schema is intended to be extensible to serve site-local needs, and can be used to constrain 
generated documents for the initial ingest of 
records into OLE.  Another goal is to provide a base schema for documents that output "live" circulation 
information for discovery systems. 
            
While this schema has not been explicitly designed to play a role in data binding (such as JAXB), it
doesn't actively discourage any such activity.

Element ole:instance / ole:resourceIdentifier
Namespace http://ole.kuali.org/standards/ole-instance
Annotations
 
Bibliographic identifier from 001 in the marc record in OLE. Multiple
values can be recorded for bound-with items.
                            
Generally required unless the context indicates the bib record-instance
relationship in some other fashion, e.g. by embedding bib records and their
associated instance records inside a parent-child structure, such as<bibWithInstances>
 ... bib data
 <instanceCollection>
  <instance>
  <instance>
 </instanceCollection>
</bibWithInstances>Such a structure might be required when ingesting new bib recors with instances,
where the system has not yet assigned a value into the 001.
Diagram
Type xs:string
Properties
content simple
minOccurs 0
maxOccurs unbounded
Source
 
<xs:element type="xs:string" name="resourceIdentifier" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
  <xs:annotation>
    <xs:documentation>Bibliographic identifier from 001 in the marc record in OLE. Multiple values can be recorded for bound-with items. Generally required unless the context indicates the bib record-instance relationship in some other fashion, e.g. by embedding bib records and their associated instance records inside a parent-child structure, such as
      <![CDATA[
                              <bibWithInstances>
                               ... bib data
                               <instanceCollection>
                                <instance>
                                <instance>
                               </instanceCollection>
                              </bibWithInstances>
                            ]]>Such a structure might be required when ingesting new bib recors with instances, where the system has not yet assigned a value into the 001.</xs:documentation>
  </xs:annotation>
</xs:element>

Element ole:oleHoldings / ole:receiptStatus
Namespace http://ole.kuali.org/standards/ole-instance
Annotations
 
Receipt status, by default equivalent to MFHD 008 position 6
 
0 - Unknown 
1 - Other receipt or acquisition status 
2 - Received and complete or ceased 
3 - On order 
4 - Currently received 
5 - Not currently received
                        
The actual list of values is maintained separately from the schema.
Diagram
Type restriction of ole:codedValue
Type hierarchy
  • ole:codedValue
Properties
content complex
Attributes
QName Type Use Annotation
code ole:receiptStatusCode required 
The code for the receipt status (see above numeric values for defaults);
the list of allowed values is managed outside this schema.
                                    
See ole:receiptStatusCode documentation for more information.
Source

                        3 - On order

                        The actual list of values is maintained separately from the schema. 
                        
                       
                    </xs:documentation>

Element ole:item / ole:analytic
Namespace http://ole.kuali.org/standards/ole-instance
Annotations
 
Identifies another system holdings record (via the system identifier) to which this
item is linked, as with, e.g. individual monographs that are members of a series.  
                        
This mechanism is different from bound-withs in that it links this *item* to a different 
*holdings* instead of to another bibliographic record.
                        
For example, if the containing item's bib record identifies a monograph (M) that belongs to a 
monographic series (MS), then both M and MS will have their own bibliographic records, and MS 
will have at least one holdings record.  The value of this element would be the system
assigned identifier for MS' holdings record.

Complex Type ole:instance
Namespace http://ole.kuali.org/standards/ole-instance
Annotations
 
An instance is a conceptual grouping of holdings and item information
together.  
                    
At most one holdings element can be present, and in the base schema takes
the form of either an "OLE native" format or a MARC For Holdings Description 
(MFHD) XML record.
                    
Fields that are valid for both holdings and item elements are generally expected to 
be inheritable, i.e. if callNumber is set on holdings, all items that dont' specify
a call number will use that value.
Diagram
Used by
Element ole:instance
Model

If true, indicates that this instance should not be displayed to the public.

<xs:complexType name="oleHoldings">
  <xs:annotation>
    <xs:documentation>OLE native holdings; this can be used if not using some other standard for holdings (e.g. MFHD)</xs:documentation>
  </xs:annotation>
  <xs:sequence>
    <xs:element type="xs:token" name="holdingsIdentifier" minOccurs="0">
      <xs:annotation>
        <xs:documentation>The system generated unique ID for the holdings record; may be omitted during initial ingest, before the record has such an identifier.</xs:documentation>
      </xs:annotation>
    </xs:element>
    <xs:element type="ole:extentOfOwnership" name="extentOfOwnership" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1">
      <xs:annotation>
        <xs:documentation>Wrapper element containing either summary textual holdings statements equivalent to MFHD 866, 867, and 868 (http://www.loc.gov/marc/holdings/hd866868.html) OR detailed structured coverage information (dates, volumes, issues) of the sort usually associated with electronic resources.</xs:documentation>
      </xs:annotation>
    </xs:element>
    <xs:element name="receiptStatus">
      <xs:annotation>
        <xs:documentation xml:space="preserve">
                        Receipt status, by default equivalent to MFHD 008 position 6
                         
                        0 - Unknown 
                        1 - Other receipt or acquisition status 
                        2 - Received and complete or ceased 
                        3 - On order 
                        4 - Currently received 
                        5 - Not currently received
                        
                        The actual list of values is maintained separately from the schema. 
                        
                       
                    </xs:documentation>
      </xs:annotation>
      <xs:complexType>
        <xs:complexContent>
          <xs:restriction base="ole:codedValue">
            <xs:attribute name="code" use="required" type="ole:receiptStatusCode">
              <xs:annotation>
                <xs:documentation xml:space="preserve">
                                    The code for the receipt status (see above numeric values for defaults);
                                    the list of allowed values is managed outside this schema.
                                    
                                    See ole:receiptStatusCode documentation for more information.
                                </xs:documentation>
              </xs:annotation>
            </xs:attribute>
          </xs:restriction>
        </xs:complexContent>
      </xs:complexType>
    </xs:element>
    <xs:element name="subscriptionStatus" type="ole:subscriptionStatus" minOccurs="0">
      <xs:annotation>
        <xs:documentation>Subscription status for electronic resources. Related to, but distinct from receiptStatus.</xs:documentation>

    </xs:element>

        <xs:documentation>Specify either a location by reference (locationRef) or hierarchically</xs:documentation>
      </xs:annotation>
    </xs:group>
    <xs:element name="uri" type="ole:uri" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
      <xs:annotation>
        <xs:documentation>URI usually used for accessing the resource. We should probab</xs:documentation>
      </xs:annotation>
    </xs:element>
    <xs:element name="accessInformation" type="ole:accessInformation" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded">
      <xs:annotation>
        <xs:documentation>Information required to access the item electronically. AJC -- we are investigating whether bare ole:uri is sufficient here instead of accessInformation one possible use case is e-books with simultaneous user restrictions catalogued as items; if e-books can only be catalogued as holdings, though, ole:uri would probably work here.</xs:documentation>
      </xs:annotation>
    </xs:element>
    <xs:element name="callNumber" type="ole:callNumber">
      <xs:annotation>
        <xs:documentation>Call number information that will be inherited by any contained items unless overridden at the item level.</xs:documentation>
      </xs:annotation>
    </xs:element>

Simple Type ole:textualHoldingsCodeType
Namespace http://ole.kuali.org/standards/ole-instance
Annotations
 
Extensible base type for indicating type of textual holdings statement 
By default, allowable values are "Basic Bibliographic Unit", "Supplementary Material", "Indexes" 
corresponding to MFHD 866, 867, and 868.
                
However, the list of allowable values is locally overridable via externally maintained data in OLE (see appinfo for details)
and so this schema does not provide any actual enumeration of allowed values.

Complex Type ole:dateSpecification
Namespace http://ole.kuali.org/standards/ole-instance
Annotations
 
A type that allows specifying a date a one of four levels of resolution, including full date, year and month, year and quarter, just year, or
*offset*, which is typically used for rolling coverage end dates with embargoes (e.g. "coverage extends up to a month ago")

Children ole:dateOffset, ole:fullDate, ole:quarterYear, ole:year, ole:yearAndMonth
Source
 
<xs:complexType name="dateSpecification">
  <xs:annotation>
    <xs:documentation>A type that allows specifying a date a one of four levels of resolution, including full date, year and month, year and quarter, just year, or *offset*, which is typically used for rolling coverage end dates with embargoes (e.g. "coverage extends up to a month ago")</xs:documentation>
  </xs:annotation>
  <xs:choice>
    <xs:element name="fullDate" type="xs:date"/>
    <xs:element name="yearAndMonth" type="xs:gYearMonth"/>
    <xs:element name="year" type="xs:gYear"/>
    <xs:element name="quarterYear">
      <xs:annotation>
        <xs:documentation>Specifies a year in the element content, and which quarter in the @quarter attribute, e.g. Q1 2015 is represented as <ole:quarterYear quarter="1">2015</ole:quarterYear></xs:documentation>
      </xs:annotation>
      <xs:complexType>
        <xs:simpleContent>
          <xs:extension base="xs:gYear">
            <xs:attribute name="quarter" use="required">
              <xs:simpleType>
                <xs:restriction base="xs:positiveInteger">
                  <xs:minInclusive value="1"/>
                  <xs:maxInclusive value="4"/>
                </xs:restriction>
              </xs:simpleType>
            </xs:attribute>
          </xs:extension>
        </xs:simpleContent>
      </xs:complexType>
    </xs:element>
    <xs:element name="dateOffset" type="xs:duration">
      <xs:annotation>
        <xs:documentation>Offset, typically used for embargoes on end dates, e.g. "coverage extends up to 3 months ago", which would take the form "-P3M"</xs:documentation>
      </xs:annotation>
    </xs:element>
  </xs:choice>
</xs:complexType>

Complex Type ole:uri
Namespace http://ole.kuali.org/standards/ole-instance
Annotations
 
The URI(s) from 856$u and $y.  The href attribute is required and maps to 856$u; the content of this 
element maps to 856$y.
                
Defined as a string so as to avoid validation failures when the indicated field does not contain
a syntatically valid URI; if you would like to use your ingest process as an opportunity to perform
data cleanup, you might redefined this as xs:anyURI in your customization.

to the difference between URL and URN).  Defaults to "true".
